{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8ff4f1badd284859", "type": "tool_result", "content": "200\tThe speaker whose enrollment embedding yields the highest similarity to the mixture is designated as the dominant speaker.\n201\tThe dominant speaker retains the original mixture segment in the corresponding ASR input, while the other speaker removes that overlapped region from their ASR segments.\n202\t\n203\tTABLE II: Diarization system comparison on Track 2 development set.\n204\t\n205\tSystem\n206\tMISS\n207\tSPK\n208\tDER\n209\ttcpCER\n210\t\n211\tOpen-source DiariZen\n212\t | 8.79\n213\t | 6.69\n214\t | 22.44\n215\t | 27.26\n216\t\n217\tSmartGlasses-only DiariZen\n218\t | 5.39\n219\t | 8.43\n220\t | 21.07\n221\t | 29.74\n222\t\n223\tOpen-data + SmartGlasses\n224\t | 7.21\n225\t | 4.57\n226\t | 18.62\n227\t | 22.88\n228\t\n229\tTABLE III: TSE model comparison on Track 2 development set.\n230\t\n231\tTSE model\n232\ttcpCER\n233\tWER\n234\t\n235\tLarge-scale SV-trained TSE\n236\t | 24.69\n237\t | 20.60\n238\t\n239\tSmartGlasses-adapted TSE\n240\t | 23.64\n241\t | 19.80\n242\t\n243\tTABLE IV: Overlap strategy comparison on Track 2 development set, based on experimental verification with Qwen3-ASR-1.7b.\n244\t\n245\tStrategy\n246\tMISS\n247\tSPK\n248\tDER\n249\ttcpCER\n250\t\n251\tNative segmentation\n252\t | 5.07\n253\t | 5.16\n254\t | 17.53\n255\t | 26.64\n256\t\n257\tDrop overlap\n258\t | 27.33\n259\t | 2.06\n260\t | 34.54\n261\t | 32.88\n262\t\n263\tAssign overlap\n264\t | 15.16\n265\t | 3.56\n266\t | 23.95\n267\t | 25.78\n268\t\n269\tTSE overlap\n270\t | 5.07\n271\t | 5.16\n272\t | 17.53\n273\t | 24.69\n274\t\n275\tTSE dominant overlap\n276\t | 7.21\n277\t | 4.57\n278\t | 18.62\n279\t | 22.88\n280\t\n281\tTABLE V: Channel and ASR comparisons on Track 2 development set. The channel results are obtained using FireRedASR2-AED under the TSE overlap configuration. DER collar is 0s\n282\t\n283\tFactor\n284\tSystem\n285\t | DER\n286\t | tcpCER\n287\t\n288\tChannel\n289\tch1\n290\t | 17.53\n291\t | 23.61\n292\t\n293\tch2\n294\t | 17.81\n295\t | 24.09\n296\t\n297\tch3\n298\t | 18.12\n299\t | 24.32\n300\t\n301\tch4\n302\t | 18.50\n303\t | 25.25\n304\t\n305\tBaseline\n306\tVibevoice-ASR\n307\t | 32.50\n308\t | 33.77\n309\t\n310\tASR\n311\tQwen3-ASR-1.7B\n312\t | -\n313\t | 22.88\n314\t\n315\tFireRedASR2-AED\n316\t | -\n317\t | 21.73\n318\t\n319\tIII-E ASR Model Selection\n320\t\n321\tThe post-processed speaker-specific segments are finally passed to the ASR backend.\n322\tWe evaluate Qwen3-ASR-1.7b [14] and FireRedASR2-AED [19]. Qwen3-ASR-1.7b is used for fast development experiments due to its inference speed, which enables rapid iteration. For the final submission, we adopt FireRedASR2-AED, as it achieves lower tcpCER.\n323\t\n324\tIV Experiments\n325\t\n326\tIV-A Model parameter sizes\n327\t\n328\tWe explicitly declare that the total parameter size does not exceed 35B. The diarization model, consisting of WavLM-Large and a Conformer backend, contains 321.8M parameters. The TSE model, based on BSRNN with ECAPA conditioning, contains 27.6M parameters. The FireRedASR2-AED, contains 1,183M parameters. Therefore, the total number of parameters is 1,532.4M.\n329\t\n330\tIV-B Experimental Setup\n331\t\n332\tThe diarization model is trained for 30 epochs. WavLM is frozen for the first two epochs and then jointly optimized with the backend, using learning rates of 1e-5 and 1e-3 for WavLM and the remaining components, respectively. Noise augmentation starts from epoch 6 for single-noise and epoch 15 for mixed-noise conditions. The TSE model is pre-trained on a speaker-verification corpus and fine-tuned on the official SmartGlasses training data with learning rates of 1e-3 and 1e-4, respectively. The unreliable-extraction threshold is tuned on the development set and set to 0.55.\n333\t\n334\tIV-C Development Results\n335\t\n336\tTable II compares diarization systems.\n337\tThe open-source baseline [9] has the highest DER and tcpCER.\n338\tThe SmartGlasses-only model reduces MISS but has high speaker confusion and poor tcpCER. The final open-data plus SmartGlasses model has the best overall tcpCER among the three systems.\n339\tTable III compares the two TSE models using the same diarization and ASR setup. The SmartGlasses-adapted TSE model has almost unchanged DER but reduces tcpCER from 24.69% to 23.64%, showing that adaptation mainly improves the ASR quality of separated overlap speech.\n340\t\n341\tTable IV compares overlap handling strategies. Native segmentation directly feeds diarization outputs to ASR. Dropping all overlap severely increases MISS. Assigning overlap to a single speaker reduces insertions but loses much target speech. For TSE overlap, we extract speaker-specific signals for each speaker in overlap and feed them to ASR directly. Our proposed TSE dominant overlap adds a fallback: when the two extracted signals are too similar, we assign the original mixture to the speaker whose enrollment embedding is most similar to it, and drop that region for the other speaker.\n342\tThis achieves the best development-set result, reducing tcpCER from 24.69% to 22.88%.\n343\tTable V summarizes channel and ASR comparisons. Among the four single channels, channel 1 gives the lowest tcpCER. With the same diarization and TSE configuration, FireRedASR2-AED reduces tcpCER from 22.88% to 21.73% compared with Qwen3-ASR-1.7b, so it is used in our final system.\n344\t\n345\tIV-D Official Test Result\n346\t\n347\tOn the official test set, the final system achieves a tcpCER of 7.10% on Track 1, ranking fifth on the Track 1 leaderboard, and a tcpCER of 34.04% on Track 2, ranking second on the Track 2 leaderboard.\n348\t\n349\tV Conclusion\n350\t\n351\tThis paper presented the tttAI system for the TSA-ASR task of the SmartGlasses Challenge 2026.\n352\tThe system follows a cascaded speaker-attributed ASR pipeline with diarization, overlap-aware target-speaker extraction, post-processing, and FireRedASR2-AED.\n353\tOfficial test results show that our system achieves a tcpCER of 7.10% on Track 1 and a tcpCER of 34.04% on Track 2, ranking second on the Track 2 leaderboard.\n354\t\n355\tReferences\n356\t\n357\t[1]\n358\tJ. Carletta, S. Ashby, S. Bourban, M. Flynn, M. Guillemot, T. Hain, J. Kadlec, V. Karaiskos, W. Kraaij, M. Kronenthal, et al. (2005)\n359\t\n360\tThe ami meeting corpus: a pre-announcement.\n361\t\n362\tIn International workshop on machine learning for multimodal interaction,\n363\t\n364\t pp. 28–39.\n365\t\n366\tCited by: §III-A.\n367\t\n368\t[2]\n369\tS. Chen, C. Wang, Z. Chen, Y. Wu, S. Liu, Z. Chen, J. Li, N. Kanda, T. Yoshioka, X. Xiao, et al. (2022)\n370\t\n371\tWavLM: large-scale self-supervised pre-training for full stack speech processing.\n372\t\n373\tIEEE Journal of Selected Topics in Signal Processing 16 (6), pp. 1505–1518.\n374\t\n375\tCited by: §I.\n376\t\n377\t[3]\n378\tJ. S. Chung, J. Huh, A. Nagrani, T. Afouras, and A. Zisserman (2020)\n379\t\n380\tSpot the conversation: speaker diarisation in the wild.\n381\t\n382\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2007.01216.\n383\t\n384\tCited by: §III-A.\n385\t\n386\t[4]\n387\tB. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck (2020)\n388\t\n389\tEcapa-tdnn: emphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in tdnn based speaker verification.\n390\t\n391\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2005.07143.\n392\t\n393\tCited by: §I,\n394\t§III-C.\n395\t\n396\t[5]\n397\tY. Fu, L. Cheng, S. Lv, Y. Jv, Y. Kong, Z. Chen, Y. Hu, L. Xie, J. Wu, H. Bu, et al. (2021)\n398\t\n399\tAishell-4: an open source dataset for speech enhancement, separation, recognition and speaker diarization in conference scenario.\n400\t\n401\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2104.03603.\n402\t\n403\tCited by: §III-A.\n404\t\n405\t[6]\n406\tY. Fujita, N. Kanda, S. Horiguchi, Y. Xue, K. Nagamatsu, and S. Watanabe (2019)\n407\t\n408\tEnd-to-end neural speaker diarization with self-attention.\n409\t\n410\tIn 2019 IEEE Automatic Speec